06456nam a22008535i 9781478009122DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019027310  a97814780091227 a10.1515/97814780091222doi  a(DE-B1597)554578  a(OCoLC)1170300535  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aML3916 7aMUS0250002bisacsh04a781.3/622300aPlaying for Keeps :bImprovisation in the Aftermath /ced. by Eric Porter, Daniel Fischlin. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aImprovisation, community, and social practice : 4500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPlaying for Keeps -- tOne. Manifesto -- tTwo. The Exhibition of Vandalizim -- tThree. The Rigors of Afro/Canarian Jazz -- tFour. “Opening Up a Space That Maybe Wouldn’t Exist Otherwise” / Holding It Down in the Aftermath -- tFive. Experimental and Improvised Norths -- tSix. Nina Simone -- tSeven. Free Improvised Music in Postwar Beirut -- tEight. Street Concerts and Sexual Harassment in Post-Mubarak Egypt -- tNine. Improvisation, Grounded Humanity, and Witnessing in Palestine -- tTen. Silsulim (Improvised “Curls”) in the Vocal Performance of Israeli Popular Music -- tEleven. Three Moments in Kī Hō‘alu (Hawaiian Slack Key Guitar) -- tTwelve. From Prepeace to Postconflict -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors to Playing for Keeps examine the ways in which musical improvisation can serve as a method for negotiating violence, trauma, systemic inequality, and the aftermaths of war and colonialism. Outlining the relation of improvisatory practices to local and global power structures, they show how in sites as varied as South Africa, Canada, Egypt, the United States, and the Canary Islands, improvisation provides the means for its participants to address the past and imagine the future. In addition to essays, the volume features a poem by saxophonist Matana Roberts, an interview with pianist Vijay Iyer about his work with U.S. veterans of color, and drawings by artist Randy DuBurke that chart Nina Simone's politicization. Throughout, the contributors illustrate how improvisation functions as a model for political, cultural, and ethical dialogue and action that can foster the creation of alternate modes of being and knowing in the world.Contributors. Randy DuBurke, Rana El Kadi, Kevin Fellezs, Daniel Fischlin, Kate Galloway, Reem Abdul Hadi, Vijay Iyer, Mark Lomanno, Moshe Morad, Eric Porter, Sara Ramshaw, Matana Roberts, Darci Sprengel, Paul Stapleton, Odeh Turjman, Stephanie Vos  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aImprovisation (Music)xPolitical aspects. 0aImprovisation (Music)xSocial aspects. 0aImprovisation (Music)-Political aspects. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh1 aDuBurke, Randy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFellezs, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischlin, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischlin, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGalloway, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIyer, Vijay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKadi, Rana El, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLomanno, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorad, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPorter, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPorter, Eric, eedit